WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.600
Hi everyone, my name is Davis Vaughan, I'm here with my colleague Lionel Henry and we're

00:00:08.600 --> 00:00:12.320
here to talk to you about a new tool we've created called Air.

00:00:12.320 --> 00:00:15.640
Actually the warm-up music there was also a band called Air.

00:00:15.640 --> 00:00:18.840
It's a French band, which is also where we got these t-shirts from.

00:00:18.840 --> 00:00:24.920
When you choose a generic name you can co-op swag from other people, which is quite nice.

00:00:24.920 --> 00:00:28.600
So what I want to start with is to have you just look at this kind of prose here on the

00:00:28.600 --> 00:00:29.600
left.

00:00:29.600 --> 00:00:32.919
Besides it being in Latin, what you should understand is that it's just kind of hard

00:00:32.919 --> 00:00:36.880
to read because there's no white space.

00:00:36.880 --> 00:00:38.279
Compare that to this on the right.

00:00:38.279 --> 00:00:41.279
We have a lot of white space, we have a lot of indentation, bolding.

00:00:41.279 --> 00:00:46.799
It just makes the prose a lot easier to read, a lot more pleasant.

00:00:46.799 --> 00:00:49.080
And code is kind of the same way.

00:00:49.080 --> 00:00:50.480
Here's a for loop.

00:00:50.480 --> 00:00:51.480
It's compressed.

00:00:51.480 --> 00:00:53.119
We've all seen code like this, right?

00:00:53.119 --> 00:00:56.919
If I were to ask you on a glance, what does this do, you don't necessarily know.

00:00:56.919 --> 00:01:00.799
There might be hidden bugs, it's hard to find it out.

00:01:00.799 --> 00:01:07.000
Compare that to rewriting this for loop with some good indentation, some good spacing,

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:10.800
lots of new lines, and now it's really easy to see that this just prints out.

00:01:10.800 --> 00:01:13.519
It's even or it's odd.

00:01:13.519 --> 00:01:18.680
Now I think we can all agree this looks better than what we just saw on the previous slide.

00:01:18.680 --> 00:01:23.839
The hard part is that sometimes it's just manual or a tedious process to make your code

00:01:23.839 --> 00:01:26.879
pretty, to get it in this form.

00:01:26.879 --> 00:01:32.239
For example, watch me kind of struggle through formatting this pipeline.

00:01:32.239 --> 00:01:35.559
It extends off the right-hand side of the screen.

00:01:35.559 --> 00:01:42.040
So what I'll first do is just kind of reflow the pipes manually, and then I'll go through

00:01:42.040 --> 00:01:49.919
and expand this pivot longer call.

00:01:49.919 --> 00:01:52.400
I think we can agree, again, that this looks better in the end.

00:01:52.400 --> 00:01:54.500
You can actually read the code now.

00:01:54.500 --> 00:01:56.080
But this kind of sucks.

00:01:56.080 --> 00:02:00.040
It's a manual process, it's tedious, and at the end of a long workday, like, I'm just

00:02:00.040 --> 00:02:03.160
going to stop doing this at some point.

00:02:03.160 --> 00:02:04.160
So let's reset.

00:02:04.160 --> 00:02:11.639
Wouldn't it be cool if there was a tool where you could just snap your fingers and it would

00:02:11.639 --> 00:02:15.080
reflow the pipes?

00:02:15.080 --> 00:02:23.619
Or you could snap your fingers again and it would expand your function calls.

00:02:23.619 --> 00:02:29.339
If that sounds interesting to you, then you are really going to like Air.

00:02:29.339 --> 00:02:31.259
Air is an R code formatter.

00:02:31.259 --> 00:02:34.919
If you're not familiar with formatters, they do what you saw on the previous slide.

00:02:34.919 --> 00:02:39.899
They take messy code and they automatically turn it into pretty styled code.

00:02:39.899 --> 00:02:44.220
Now I like to think of it as giving you a whole bunch of formatting superpowers.

00:02:44.220 --> 00:02:45.740
You saw a couple on the previous slide.

00:02:45.740 --> 00:02:48.740
We'll explore more over the next following slides.

00:02:48.740 --> 00:02:51.979
And if it seems cool to you, but you're thinking, like, God, is this one more tool that I have

00:02:52.059 --> 00:02:53.059
to learn?

00:02:53.059 --> 00:02:54.059
Is this going to have a big setup curve?

00:02:54.059 --> 00:02:57.460
Am I going to have to worry about a whole bunch of things that I have to read?

00:02:57.460 --> 00:03:02.220
Well, know that we've made Air extremely simple to get going with.

00:03:02.220 --> 00:03:04.820
There's really only two steps.

00:03:04.820 --> 00:03:13.100
You configure your project to use Air, and then you format all of your existing files.

00:03:13.100 --> 00:03:17.779
And it's actually so easy to get started, we're just going to show you real quick what

00:03:17.779 --> 00:03:19.979
it looks like.

00:03:19.979 --> 00:03:26.100
So if we jump over into Positron, the thing to know is that Positron comes batteries included

00:03:26.100 --> 00:03:27.100
with Air.

00:03:27.100 --> 00:03:29.619
There's actually nothing else you need to install.

00:03:29.619 --> 00:03:31.899
It's already there.

00:03:31.899 --> 00:03:34.380
So we've got a project here with a couple files.

00:03:34.380 --> 00:03:38.339
We need to configure this project to use Air, and then we'll format those files.

00:03:38.339 --> 00:03:41.259
That's our goal for today.

00:03:41.259 --> 00:03:48.179
So the first thing we do is run this command, Air initialize workspace folder.

00:03:48.179 --> 00:03:54.100
What this will do is create those setup files that I was talking about.

00:03:54.100 --> 00:04:00.500
All this really does is tell your IDE, hey, go please use Air when you format.

00:04:00.500 --> 00:04:05.779
We'll commit those.

00:04:05.779 --> 00:04:08.059
That's step one, already done.

00:04:08.059 --> 00:04:12.259
Step two is to then go through and actually format all of the individual files, but you

00:04:12.259 --> 00:04:13.660
don't have to do that manually.

00:04:13.660 --> 00:04:14.660
We help you out.

00:04:14.660 --> 00:04:17.019
There's a button here in the bottom right-hand corner.

00:04:17.019 --> 00:04:19.940
Just click to format the whole workspace folder.

00:04:19.940 --> 00:04:23.220
That easy.

00:04:23.220 --> 00:04:27.660
So now if you use Git, and you don't have to, but if you do, and we encourage it, now

00:04:27.660 --> 00:04:31.739
you can look at the diffs of what Air has actually done to your files.

00:04:31.739 --> 00:04:34.899
It's kind of cleaned up some messy code.

00:04:34.899 --> 00:04:42.940
If you like that, then you go ahead and commit all of those, and that's step two, done.

00:04:42.940 --> 00:04:47.500
This project is now set up to work well with Air.

00:04:47.500 --> 00:04:51.619
Setting up is really easy, but again, like, okay, that's just the setup stage.

00:04:51.619 --> 00:04:53.339
What do we do on a day-to-day basis?

00:04:53.339 --> 00:04:57.700
Again, is this a tool that I have to learn a whole bunch of crap to know how to use?

00:04:57.700 --> 00:04:59.420
Well, no.

00:04:59.420 --> 00:05:05.899
We say that if you know how to save a file, you already know how to use Air.

00:05:05.899 --> 00:05:09.220
We're going to take a look at that.

00:05:09.220 --> 00:05:12.660
So we'll create a new file here in our project called visualize.r.

00:05:12.660 --> 00:05:18.619
I've already started working on some visualization code for the scripts we have here.

00:05:18.619 --> 00:05:23.980
So if I were to continue this out, I would add maybe geomline and theme minimal, and

00:05:23.980 --> 00:05:27.119
I'm not really thinking about the style of this code at this point, but it's getting

00:05:27.119 --> 00:05:28.119
pretty long.

00:05:28.119 --> 00:05:34.420
Now, I've finished my thought here, so I might take a breath and save the file.

00:05:34.420 --> 00:05:41.500
And on save, Air kicks in, and it reflows your pipes.

00:05:41.500 --> 00:05:44.940
Or I might say, well, actually, I'm not ready to do the plot yet.

00:05:44.940 --> 00:05:50.140
I need to create a couple extra columns first, so I might do a mutate call.

00:05:50.140 --> 00:05:53.299
And again, as I'm typing this, I'm not really thinking about what it looks like.

00:05:53.299 --> 00:05:54.299
I don't care at the moment.

00:05:54.299 --> 00:05:57.660
I'm just trying to get what's in my head onto the screen here.

00:05:57.660 --> 00:06:05.899
But when I finish, I take a breath, and I save, and Air kicks in, nicely reformatting

00:06:05.899 --> 00:06:10.660
this mutate call, adding white space, reflowing the pipes, and so on.

00:06:10.660 --> 00:06:16.339
And you might be thinking, like, OK, format on save, that sounds cool, but, like, every

00:06:16.339 --> 00:06:19.899
single time, like, I save hundreds or thousands of times a day, right?

00:06:19.899 --> 00:06:23.299
Like, is this going to slow me down in any way in a large file?

00:06:23.299 --> 00:06:29.140
Well, we've designed Air to be imperceptible with format on save.

00:06:29.140 --> 00:06:34.140
It is actually so fast that we want you to question whether it even ran.

00:06:34.140 --> 00:06:38.500
To put some numbers behind that, we'll look at dplyr's across.r.

00:06:38.500 --> 00:06:40.980
It has over 1,000 lines in it.

00:06:40.980 --> 00:06:43.619
It's a fairly large R file.

00:06:43.619 --> 00:06:48.579
This takes 20 seconds, or 20 milliseconds, sorry, to format with Air.

00:06:48.579 --> 00:06:51.420
That would not be fast, would it?

00:06:51.420 --> 00:06:57.299
By comparison, to just give you some relative numbers, when you blink your eye, it takes

00:06:57.299 --> 00:06:59.179
200 milliseconds.

00:06:59.179 --> 00:07:01.579
So it's very fast.

00:07:01.579 --> 00:07:03.420
Let's scale up.

00:07:03.420 --> 00:07:08.980
What if we were to format all of dplyr all at once, 150 files?

00:07:08.980 --> 00:07:12.339
That takes Air 200 milliseconds.

00:07:12.339 --> 00:07:19.220
You can format the whole project of dplyr in the blink of an eye.

00:07:19.220 --> 00:07:23.540
If that sounds cool to you, and you're considering adopting Air, know that you will be in good

00:07:23.540 --> 00:07:24.540
company.

00:07:24.540 --> 00:07:29.600
We have already transitioned most of our packages over to using it, including a number of community

00:07:29.600 --> 00:07:32.660
packages like Nanier and iGraph.

00:07:32.660 --> 00:07:36.940
At this point, Air has been run over hundreds of thousands of lines of R code.

00:07:36.940 --> 00:07:38.820
We feel pretty good about the formatting.

00:07:38.820 --> 00:07:42.260
It feels pretty stable, and we're confident about it at this point.

00:07:42.260 --> 00:07:46.579
And it's truly a great time to adopt this tool.

00:07:46.579 --> 00:07:56.820
So our goal with the formatter is that once you start using it, it will be hard for you

00:07:56.820 --> 00:08:01.179
to go back to your previous formatter-less life.

00:08:01.179 --> 00:08:05.500
And that's something that we have managed to achieve with Hadley, because now, when

00:08:05.500 --> 00:08:10.179
he saves a file and he doesn't reformat, it feels broken.

00:08:10.179 --> 00:08:15.859
So we knew that Hadley would be an easy win, because he cares a lot about style.

00:08:15.859 --> 00:08:18.779
And actually, many of us in the organization do.

00:08:18.779 --> 00:08:22.899
And I want to talk about what happens when you have a room full of programmers who all

00:08:22.899 --> 00:08:26.179
care a lot about style.

00:08:26.179 --> 00:08:28.220
Something like this happens.

00:08:28.260 --> 00:08:33.340
So these are excerpts from pull request reviews in our organization.

00:08:33.340 --> 00:08:38.739
And in all these instances, the reviewer is focused on the style of the contribution that

00:08:38.739 --> 00:08:40.739
comes in.

00:08:40.739 --> 00:08:45.900
So of course, we would prefer to focus on the content of the contribution.

00:08:45.900 --> 00:08:49.700
And we call this collaborative friction.

00:08:49.700 --> 00:08:55.080
And we think that Air can help you with collaborative friction in two ways.

00:08:55.080 --> 00:09:00.919
The first is enforcement, and the second is configuration, and we'll start with enforcement.

00:09:00.919 --> 00:09:06.000
So if you are a GitHub user, we have a GitHub action called setupAir.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:10.960
And once you've set up your project with this, a robot will come in and check the style for

00:09:10.960 --> 00:09:14.900
you, according to what Air expects.

00:09:14.900 --> 00:09:17.320
And so the robot provides suggestions.

00:09:17.320 --> 00:09:23.640
When the style doesn't match, the contributor can commit the suggestions themselves.

00:09:23.640 --> 00:09:28.200
And hopefully, with all the style comments out of the way, it will be easier and faster

00:09:28.200 --> 00:09:32.520
to get the contribution accepted in the project.

00:09:32.520 --> 00:09:33.799
So that was enforcement.

00:09:33.799 --> 00:09:37.559
Let's talk about configuration.

00:09:37.559 --> 00:09:43.280
So here we have a configuration file for a formatter called clang-format, which is for

00:09:43.280 --> 00:09:46.640
C code.

00:09:46.640 --> 00:09:50.020
And this particular formatter is extremely configurable.

00:09:50.020 --> 00:09:56.140
Here you have a small sample of the configuration options that you have to describe how you

00:09:56.140 --> 00:10:00.059
want your code to be formatted.

00:10:00.059 --> 00:10:04.859
So that's a lot of complexity and a lot of knobs to turn.

00:10:04.859 --> 00:10:10.059
Now some of you might like this flexibility, but we'd like to argue that there is a hidden

00:10:10.059 --> 00:10:12.419
cost to it.

00:10:12.419 --> 00:10:18.659
So to give you an example, here is Davis and I trying to configure a formatter for REST

00:10:18.659 --> 00:10:22.580
code, because we write a lot of REST code these days.

00:10:22.580 --> 00:10:28.460
And here I'm suggesting to use a particular option to format the REST code.

00:10:28.460 --> 00:10:33.500
And I come in as the well-actually Felice and say, I don't like this option, actually.

00:10:33.500 --> 00:10:36.380
I think it actually makes the code worse, and blah, blah, blah.

00:10:36.380 --> 00:10:41.619
And we just end up back in the same scenario before with...

00:10:41.619 --> 00:10:47.059
So that's, like, we're going back to collaborative friction again.

00:10:47.059 --> 00:10:51.119
So that's why we made the formatter more like a light switch than a sound mixer.

00:10:51.119 --> 00:10:52.659
So it's either on or off.

00:10:52.659 --> 00:10:56.979
You're either using the formatter rules that we have, or you're not.

00:10:56.979 --> 00:11:01.960
So that's how a configuration file looks like with our formatter.

00:11:01.960 --> 00:11:05.020
You have how wide you want your code to be.

00:11:05.020 --> 00:11:09.700
You have a couple of options about indentation style, whether you use spaces or tabs, and

00:11:09.700 --> 00:11:12.059
how wide an indentation is.

00:11:12.059 --> 00:11:13.059
And that's it.

00:11:13.500 --> 00:11:18.340
We hope that will make it straightforward to set up your project and agree with your

00:11:18.340 --> 00:11:22.900
collaborator how to set up the project with R.

00:11:22.900 --> 00:11:28.820
So does that mean that with this trick, a formatter, you have absolutely no say into

00:11:28.820 --> 00:11:30.619
how to format your code?

00:11:30.619 --> 00:11:32.059
Well, not quite.

00:11:32.059 --> 00:11:38.460
Because one of our design goals was to make it easy to still have some flexibility.

00:11:38.539 --> 00:11:40.619
And that happens in two ways.

00:11:40.619 --> 00:11:43.380
First, persistent line breaks and magic commands.

00:11:43.380 --> 00:11:49.380
And to give you an example for persistent line breaks, here we have a couple of R expressions,

00:11:49.380 --> 00:11:52.340
a list call and a ggplot pipeline.

00:11:52.340 --> 00:11:58.020
And the idea is that if you insert a line break in the first element of a list call,

00:11:58.020 --> 00:12:04.979
for instance, that will be taken as an instruction for the formatter to go from the flat layout

00:12:05.020 --> 00:12:07.940
to the expanded layout, which is more vertical.

00:12:07.940 --> 00:12:11.140
You can do the same with the ggplot pipeline.

00:12:11.140 --> 00:12:13.539
So you find the first element.

00:12:13.539 --> 00:12:15.219
You add a line break.

00:12:15.219 --> 00:12:16.219
You save.

00:12:16.219 --> 00:12:19.780
It reformats to the expanded layout.

00:12:19.780 --> 00:12:21.619
That works in the opposite direction as well.

00:12:21.619 --> 00:12:25.219
You can remove the line break, save, go back to flat.

00:12:25.219 --> 00:12:26.219
And same for the list call.

00:12:26.219 --> 00:12:30.299
Remove the line break, and it goes back to flat.

00:12:30.299 --> 00:12:35.419
So that's one of our favorite features with the formatter, because it really gives you

00:12:35.419 --> 00:12:37.020
a grip on your code.

00:12:37.020 --> 00:12:43.580
It's super fun to use, and we hope you will like it, too.

00:12:43.580 --> 00:12:49.039
Now another way we provide you some flexibility is magic commands.

00:12:49.039 --> 00:12:54.299
So here you have an example from igraph, which is a package for specifying graphs.

00:12:54.299 --> 00:12:58.539
And it uses operators, the minus and plus operators, to do that.

00:12:58.539 --> 00:13:01.419
So here you have a graph specification.

00:13:01.419 --> 00:13:05.619
And if you try to format this with air, there's no way that it's going to know how to do a

00:13:05.619 --> 00:13:07.619
good job with this operator.

00:13:07.619 --> 00:13:12.619
So that will not look like a proper graph anymore.

00:13:12.619 --> 00:13:15.140
So what you can do is use a magic command.

00:13:15.140 --> 00:13:17.700
In this case, it's a skip command.

00:13:17.700 --> 00:13:24.659
And that's like an instruction to ignore the next line of code and to leave it as is.

00:13:24.659 --> 00:13:30.020
So of course, if you use igraph a lot, you're not going to want to insert magic commands

00:13:30.020 --> 00:13:31.020
everywhere.

00:13:31.020 --> 00:13:35.979
So we also have a configuration option to specify which functions should be skipped

00:13:35.979 --> 00:13:40.900
by the formatter.

00:13:40.900 --> 00:13:44.979
So as we wrap up here, there's one more thing that we wanted to show you.

00:13:44.979 --> 00:13:50.659
Now all of the examples and videos so far have been in Positron.

00:13:50.659 --> 00:13:54.260
But air is an external tool.

00:13:54.260 --> 00:13:58.900
What that means is that it also works in RStudio.

00:13:58.900 --> 00:14:04.140
And in fact, air works in any IDE.

00:14:04.140 --> 00:14:09.820
If that IDE supports the language server protocol or allows for external formatters, you can

00:14:09.820 --> 00:14:11.539
use it with air.

00:14:11.539 --> 00:14:21.659
That includes NeoVim, Emacs, Elix, Zed, VS Code, Positron, RStudio, and the list goes on.

00:14:21.659 --> 00:14:24.659
You see, we want air to be a tool for the whole community.

00:14:24.659 --> 00:14:30.460
And this means providing great support for all IDEs, not just Positron and RStudio.

00:14:30.460 --> 00:14:34.979
We have guides for most or if not all of these on our website.

00:14:34.979 --> 00:14:40.179
And at the end of the day, air is for everyone, no matter where you write your R code.

00:14:40.179 --> 00:14:41.179
Thank you very much.

00:14:41.179 --> 00:14:42.179
Thank you.

00:14:42.179 --> 00:14:43.179
Thank you.

00:14:43.179 --> 00:14:44.179
Thank you.

00:14:44.179 --> 00:14:44.179


